==English==
===Etymology===
From Latin [[#Latin|infimum]] ‘lowest part’, from [[infimus]] ‘lowest’.

===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/ɪnˈfaɪməm/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|infima}}

# The ''infimum'' of a set <math>S \subset \mathbb{R}</math> is the [http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Infimum greatest lower bound] of <math>S\!\,</math>, if it exists.
# In an arbitrary partially ordered set <math>(P, \leq)\!\,</math>, the ''infimum'' of a subset <math>S\!\,</math> refers to the element (if it exists) <math>\alpha\!\,</math> satisfying
:# <math>\alpha \leq x\!\,</math> for all <math>x \in S</math>, and
:# if whenever an element <math>\beta \in S</math> satisfies <math>\beta \leq x\!\,</math> for all <math>x \in S</math>, it holds that <math>\beta \leq \alpha\!\,</math>.